orks for the three sales every early-stage founder has to win. </div><div><br/></div><div>If you&#x27;re building something technical, you already know how to speak the language of precision. This session is about learning when and how to shift toward accessibility and connection so that the people on the other side of the table understand, believe, and say yes.
<div><br/></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="event-info"><div class="md-container event-info__container"><div class="event-info__wrapper"><div class="event-info__main"><h3 class="event-info__title uppercase">Speaker</h3><div class="event-info__body"><div class="event-info__image"><img src="https://founder-nexus-storage-prod.sfo3.digitaloceanspaces.com/media/speakers/019d9d6a-421d-7180-9a45-33db967408c7.jpeg" alt="Speaker avatar" class="event-info__avatar"/><p class="event-info__quotes">“</p></div><div class="event-info__text"><h6 class="event-info__heading">Tre Balchowsky</h6><div class="mt-5">Business Storytelling Consultant. </div><div class="event-info__paragraph">Tre Balchowsky is a public speaking and storytelling coach who works with founders and executives to help them translate complex ideas and technology into stories that move people to action. <div><br/></div><div>She has coached clients through talks for TED and AWS re:Invent, high-stakes investor pitches, and the kind of early customer events that determine whether a company finds traction or stalls out. Her clients have closed significant funding rounds, built loyal audiences, and landed the talent they needed to grow, often by learning what a story actually is and how to tell one with confidence. <div><br/></div><div>With a background spanning Fortune 100 companies, major tech firms, and experimental labs, Tre brings a practitioner&#x27;s eye to the gap between what technical founders know and what their audiences can hear.
